	<h1>Welcome to Craiglickr</h1>

	<h2>Configure Craiglickr</h2>
	<p> Configuring Craiglickr is easy: </p>
	<ol>
		<li><a href="/craiglickr/locations">Pick your locations</a></li>
		<li>Pick your boards</li>
	</ol>
	<p> <a href="http://www.craigslist.org" target="_blank">Craigslist</a> is a (mostly) free community forum for posting and advertising products and services. Craiglickr is a free and open source posting tool written in perl with the <a href="http://www.catalystframework.org" target="_blank">Catalyst Web Framework</a> to ease the use of Craigslist.</p>
	<p> Craiglickr provides <a href="/static/gm/craiglickr.user.js">a Greasemonkey script</a> to ease the redundancy in posting to Craigslist. <a href="http://www.greasespot.net/" target="_blank">Greasemonkey</a> is a tool that permits control of your browser. We specifically use it to ease your experience across the domain <tt>https://post.craigslist.org</tt>. Greasemonkey require <a href="http://www.mozilla.com/en-US/products/firefox/" target="_blank">Firefox</a>, a totally free and open-source standards-compliant web browser. These are both good things and they are strongly recommended. You can <a href="http://www.firefox.com" target="_blank">download Firefox at firefox.com</a> and you can <a href="https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/748" target="_blank">download greasemonkey at addons.mozzila.org.</a></p> <p> If you're looking for more information on Greasemonkey <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greasemonkey" target="_blank">check out the Wikipedia article on it</a>; <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mozilla_Firefox" target="_blank">same goes for Firefox &mdash; check out Wikipedia for more information</a>.</p>

	<h2> Using Craiglickr </h2>
	<p>
	After Craiglickr is configured you can use it by linking to:
	<br /><tt style="font-size:large">http://craiglickrdomain.com/craiglickr/cities/*/boards/*</tt>
	<br /><em style="font-size:x-small">note: replace the * with the city or board, or in the event you wish to force Craiglickr to cross-post, a comma seperated list of the cities or boards</em>
	</p>
[% END %]
